*OUTCOMES: ES Endangered 
2 PUBLIC EDUCATION AND RECREATION: Provide Visitor Services MEASURES: 5000 new visitors will be served; 10,000 existing visitors will be served; 100 % will support the top 6 priority public uses The remote location of the Refuge makes it difficult for people to pursue wildlife dependent recreation without a campground.
Although the Refuge currently has two designated camping areas, more development of one and closure of the other is necessary to minimize issues of fire protection, habitat damage, and maintenance workload.
This project would allow site planning and development of the Crook campground including: campsite designation, tables, fire rings, pit toilets, parking areas, and vehicle barriers.
Facilities would be accessible to persons with disabilities.
Work would be contracted.
